                        <span class="text">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%" CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN=2><SPAN CLASS="header">Rating </SPAN><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/rating/9.gif" BORDER=0></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><A HREF="reportread.php3?report=37"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/read.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD><TD><A HREF="reportreview.php3?report=37"><IMG SRC="/stccg/global/images/review.gif" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><span class=header>Author</Span></TD><TD><span class=text><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=6554">Kevin "Koloth" Garrett</A></span></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Date Transmitted</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%"><span class=text>May 15, 2001</span></TD></TR><TR><TD VALIGN="TOP"><SPAN CLASS="header">Report</SPAN></TD><TD WIDTH="90%" ><span class=text>The following is the Tournament Report as written by Jeff Johnfauno, Ambassador to Veridian III.<br>
<br>
Submitted by Kevin W Garrett (aka Koloth)<br>
<br>
***********************************************************<br>
<br>
15 players showed up at Downtown Comics 3 in Carmel, IN for the 2nd Annual Star Trek CCG Indiana State Championship.  Some *very* new players (although I think everyone had played in at least one tournament before)...some veterans (including the reigning World Champion).  Several strong players had potential for making it to the final confrontation, but the favorites were Eric Johnfauno and Kevin Garrett.<br>
<br>
Most of the players were from the Indianapolis Metro area, and surrounding cities, but a few made a significant drive from the extremities of the state.<br>
<br>
The tourney was scheduled to being at 11:00, but (of course) many players didn&#146;t have their decklists complete (despite several notices vie e-mail before the event), so we actually started around 11:30.<br>
<br>
First round saw a good mix of veteran players paired against newer players (saves the more suspenseful games for later).  Of the 7 games, 5 of them were won 100-0:<br>
Jason Carrington<br>
Tyler Fultz<br>
Kevin Garrett<br>
Eric Johnfauno<br>
William Lloyd.<br>
<br>
Second round ended with 4 still undefeated players:<br>
Jason Carrington 4(+200)<br>
Kevin Garrett 4(+200)<br>
Jon Helms 3(+140)<br>
Eric Johnfauno 4(+200).<br>
<br>
In the 3rd round, the computer managed to keep Eric and Kevin from playing each other once again.  This round resulted in just 2 undefeated (and unscored against) players:<br>
Kevin Garrett<br>
Eric Johnfauno.<br>
<br>
There was just no getting around it in the 4th round...the 2 highest-rated players in Indiana were going to battle it out.  Eric had been winning his games faster...Kevin&#146;s games slower, but still holding his opponents scoreless.  I was very interested to see this game played out.  Although<br>
the game lasted a good part of the alotted time, there were actually only 5 or 6 turns (maybe less).  When the missions were tallied, and the cards cleared, the victor was Kevin 100-10.  This round ended with the following standings:<br>
1. Kevin Garrett 8(+390)<br>
2. Eric Johnfauno 6(+210)<br>
3. Mark Campbell 6(+55)<br>
4. Jason Carrington 5(+175)<br>
5. William Lloyd 5(+164)<br>
6. David Neal 4(+44)<br>
7. Tyler Fultz 4(+25)<br>
8. John Timothy 4(-75)<br>
9. Matt Noland 4(-105)<br>
10. Justin Stauffer 3(+13)<br>
11. Jon Helms 3(-27)<br>
12. William Dupree 2(-104)<br>
13. Jay Edwards 2(-212)<br>
14. John Kyle 2(-265)<br>
15. David Ford 2(-288)<br>
<br>
Continuing on to round 5, Kevin, Eric, Jason, Justin, John, and Jon all pulled out perfect 100-0 wins.  There was an interesting occurrence this round...William Dupree wanted to surrender, but couldn&#146;t say &quot;Devidian Door&quot; because he didn&#146;t have any personnel or equipment cards to play! :-)<br>
<br>
Going in to round 6, Kevin was assured a seat in the final confrontation.  The other seat was up for grabs between Jason, Eric, and Tyler.  Kevin defeated Jason 100-0, knocking him out of contention.  If Eric lost by<br>
100, and Tyler won by 100, there would have been an 8(+210) tie between them. Fortunately, to avoid any headaches on my part, Eric beat Mark 100-0, establishing the matchup for the final.<br>
<br>
As both Kevin and Eric finished their 6th round games quickly, they agreed to start the final confrontation game while the others were still finishing their 6th round games.  I&#146;m sure both players went into the match deep in thought as to how to alter their strategy, based on the knowledge they gained from their first meeting.  Eric had several questions for me before and during the game. (No, points from Mandarin Bailiff don&#146;t count toward the more than 15 for Writ of Accountability).  Kevin sacrificed a few personnel to trigger Eric&#146;s Friendly Fires, while Eric lost (or was greatly slowed down) by Kevin&#146;s Q-Flash.  In a desperate final attempt, Eric returned his personnel-packed ship to his hand with Space-Time Portal, then Devidian Door&#146;d Leck to Kevin&#146;s Outpost (or ship, I can&#146;t remember), and killed what he hoped to be an essential personnel.  It ended up being one Kevin&#146;s of Kevin&#146;s 3 Honor in play needed for Distress Mission.  On Kevin&#146;s turn, he discarded Assign Mission Specialists (time to get another more Honor mission specialists), but when he attempted to play another copy of AMS, Eric responded with an Energy Vortex, returning the AMS to Kevin&#146;s hand and forcing him to play another card. Kevin could make no more progress this turn, so he ended.  Eric once again dumped several personnel in his turn, but it was evident on his face that he had very few options.  Eric then announced that he was done, and said that he was not going to show the Devidian Door, thus ending the match (that Kevin would have won on his next turn anyway).<br>
<br>
So, the 2001 Indiana State Champion is Kevin Garrett Congratulations!!!<br>
<br>
The final standings:<br>
1. Kevin Garrett 12(+590) Klingon<br>
2. Eric Johnfauno 10(+410) Ferengi<br>
3. Jason Carrington 7(+175) Klingon<br>
4. Justin Stauffer 7(+114) Bajoran<br>
5. Tyler Fultz 6(+109) Romulan<br>
6. David Neal 6(-1) Romulan<br>
7. John Kyle 6(-90) Federation<br>
8. Matt Noland 6(-100) Romulan<br>
9. Mark Campbell 6(-145) Federation<br>
10. William Lloyd 5(+19) Federation<br>
11. Jon Helms 5(+18) Federation<br>
12. John Timothy 5(-115) Borg<br>
13. William Dupree 4(-204) Federation<br>
14. Jay Edwards 4(-287) Ferengi<br>
15. David Ford 2(-488) Federation<br>
<br>
Thanks to Rick and Downtown Comics for providing a great place to play, and for supplying lunch to all the players (that was a BIG sandwich!!!).<br>
<br>
<br>
Jeff Johnfauno<br>
STCCG Ambassador to Veridian III<br>
